===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To follow behind (someone or something); to tail (someone or something).
#: {{ux|en|The hunters '''trailed''' their prey deep into the woods.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To drag (something) behind on the ground.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1896| chapter=| author=Henry Wadsworth Longfellow| title=The Poetical Works of Henry Wadsworth Longfellow|editor=| page=287| passage=Our little life is but a gust That bends the branches of thy tree, And '''trails''' its blossoms in the dust! }}
#: {{ux|en|You'll get your coat all muddy if you '''trail''' it around like that.}}
#* '''1922''', {{w|Virginia Woolf}}, ''{{w|Jacob's Room}}'' Chapter 1
#*: "I saw your brother—I saw your brother," he said, nodding his head, as Archer lagged past him, '''trailing''' his spade, and scowling at the old gentleman in spectacles.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To leave (a trail of).
#: {{ux|en|He walked into the house, soaking wet, and '''trailed''' water all over the place.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To show a [[trailer]] of (a film, TV show etc.); to release or publish a preview of (a report etc.) in advance of the full publication.
#: {{ux|en|His new film was '''trailed''' on TV last night.}}
#: {{ux|en|There were no surprises in this morning's much-'''trailed''' budget statement.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To hang or drag loosely behind; to move with a slow sweeping motion.
#: ''The bride's long dress '''trailed''' behind her as she walked down the aisle.''
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1871| title=Henry Wadsworth Longfellow|author=The Divine Tragedy| page=| passage=Even now I behold a sign, A threatening of wrath divine, A watery, wandering star, through whose streaming hair, and the white Unfolding garments of light, That '''trail''' behind it afar, The constellations shine!}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[run]] or [[climb]] like certain [[plant]]s.
#* {{quote-book|en|author={{w|J.R.R. Tolkien}}|title={{w|The Fellowship of the Ring}}|chapter=I: A Long-Expected Party|series={{w|The Lord of the Rings}}|isbn=9780345339706|date=29 July 1954|seriesvolume=1|passage= The flowers glowed red and golden: snapdragons and sunflowers, and [[nasturtians]] '''trailing''' all over the turf walls and peeping in at the round windows. }}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To drag oneself lazily or reluctantly along.
#: ''Our parents marched to church and we '''trailed''' behind.''
# To be [[lose|losing]], to be behind in a competition.
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=December 29, 2011|author=Keith Jackson|work=Daily Record
|title=[http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/football/spl/celtic/2011/12/29/spl-celtic-1-rangers-0-86908-23665738/ SPL: Celtic 1 Rangers 0]
|passage=Neil Lennon and his players have, in almost no time at all, roared back from '''trailing''' Rangers by 15 points in November to ending the year two points clear.}}
# {{lb|en|military}} To carry (a firearm) with the [[breech]] near the ground and the upper part inclined forward, the piece being held by the right hand near the middle.
# To create a trail in.
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1893|month=August|work=The Century |title=The White Islander|author=Mary Hartwell Catherwood|volume=|number=|passage=The sun shone on burnished bodies and arm-bands, and robes of beaver '''trailed''' the grass as majestic fellows trod back and forth in the passion of eloquence.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1929 | title=Fox Hunting in Canada and Some Men who Made it |author=Frank Proctor | page=162| passage={{...}} was no mean judge of racing and, having a suspicion of the possible result, she secreted a lemon in the commodious recesses of a dress which, while the height of fashion in those times, nevertheless '''trailed''' the grass.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1975| title=Federal Procedural Forms, Lawyers Edition - Volume 14 |author=| page=241| passage=Because of the potential damages caused by social '''trailing''', regulations stipulate that all permits are void when a group obtains multiple permits for the same campground or use area for the same night.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1999 | title=Grand Staircase-Escalante National Monument|author=| page=2-19| passage=The monument would use the floowing indicators to determine when and where visitor allocations need to be made: (1) resource damage (e.g., proliferation of campsites, human waste problems, social '''trailing''' or vandalism to historical, archaeological, paleontological sites, or destruction of biological soil crusts), {{...}}}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2018| title=The Writer's Eye|author=Amy E. Weldon | page=77| passage=In my mind's eye, I looked down at the toes of high-topped, lace-up leather boots, peeking from under a long brown skirt that bent the grass sideways as it '''trailed''' the ground and tented gently outward with every step.}}
# To [[travel]] by following or creating trails.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1906 | title=The Quarterly of the Oregon Historical Society |author=| page=352| passage='''Trailed''' three miles down the North side and encamped early, making thirteen miles '''trailed''' to-day.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1915 | title=Early History of Lead Mining in the Iowa Country |author=Jacob Van der Zee | page=8| passage=In accordance with the treaty of 1842 they crossed the Missouri River to a reservation in Kansas. Poor crops, however, and a feverish climate made them unhappy in their new home: they '''trailed''' back to Iowa. }}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1935 | title=Green Hills of Africa|author=Ernest Hemmingway| page=164| passage=But we did not see him and now, in the big heat of noon, we made three long circles around some hills and finally came out into a meadow full of little, humpy Masai cattle and, leaving all shade behind, '''trailed''' back across the open country under the noon sun to the car.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1982 | title=Colorado River Country |author=David Lavender | page=144| passage=That control became visible each spring when they '''trailed''' back out of the low country to summer range.}}
# To [[transport]] ([[livestock]]) by herding it along a trail.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1939 | title=Pacific Stockman - Volumes 5-7|author=| page=| passage=One operator on the Boise Forest in Idaho reports that where he formerly marketed 80-pound lambs after '''trailing''' them 10 days from the allotment, his lambs now often tip the scales at 100 pounds or better, mainly because only one day is required to transport an entire shipment to the railroad through the use of truck pullmans.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1956| title=Back Trailing in the Heart of the Short-grass Country |author=John O. Bye | page=6| passage=Genesis, the first book of the Holy Bible, relates the earliest known instance of cattle being '''trailed''' to better grass lands (unless Noah's trip with the ark is one).}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1989| title=The Southern Frontiers, 1607-1860|author=John Solomon Otto | page=53| passage=The most impressive long-distance traders, however, were the backcountry drovers, who '''trailed''' herds of livestock up the wagon road to Philadelphia (Merrens 1964:135; Bridenbaugh 1971:138).}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2008| title=Ron Kay's Guide to Zion National Park|author=Ron Kay | page=78| passage=In all areas where trails are present, stock must remain on the trails. Free '''trailing''' or loose herding is not permitted.}}
# {{lb|en|dated}} To take advantage of the ignorance of; to impose upon.
#* '''1847''', {{w|Charlotte Brontë}}, ''{{w|Jane Eyre}}''
#*: I presently perceived she was (what is vernacularly termed) '''trailing''' Mrs. Dent; that is, playing on her ignorance.

